jsonEncode & Native Parsing (Flutter MethodChannel)

🔹 1️⃣ Default Behavior (Important)
MethodChannel uses StandardMessageCodec by default.
It automatically supports:

int
double
bool
String
List
Map
null
✅ So you can pass a Map directly.
❌ You do NOT need jsonEncode in most cases.
=====================================

🔹 2️⃣ Recommended Way (Structured Data)
Flutter
await platform.invokeMethod(
  'connectPrinter',
  {
    "ip": "192.168.1.10",
    "port": 9100,
  },
);
Kotlin
val ip = call.argument<String>("ip")
val port = call.argument<Int>("port")
✔ Clean
✔ Type-safe
✔ No manual parsing
======================================

🔹 3️⃣ When jsonEncode Is Required
Use jsonEncode only when:
Native side explicitly expects a JSON string
Working with third-party SDK that needs raw JSON
Handling complex nested objects manually
Flutter
await platform.invokeMethod(
  'sendRawJson',
  jsonEncode(data),
);
Kotlin
val jsonString = call.arguments as String
val jsonObject = JSONObject(jsonString)
======================================

🔹 4️⃣ Common Mistake
❌ Manually creating JSON string:
'{"ip":"$ip","port":$port}'
Problems:
Easy to break format
Type mismatch issues
Hard to debug
=====================================

🔹 5️⃣ Type Mapping Reminder
Dart	Kotlin
int	Int
double	Double
Map	HashMap
List	ArrayList
⚠ Be careful with numbers (sometimes safer to use Number in Kotlin).
======================================

🎯 Final Rule
✔ Prefer passing structured Map
✔ Avoid manual JSON string creation
✔ Use jsonEncode only when native side expects raw JSON
